'''Black Brothers''' was a well-known [[West Papua (region)|West Papuan]] pop group from [[Jayapura]].<ref name="lock"/><ref>Pickell, David, and Kal Muller. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=WUtz2hjvPvMC&pg=PA225 Between the Tides: An Fascinating Journey Among the Kamoro of New Guinea]''. Singapore: Periplus, 2002. p. 225</ref> The band consisted of five members,<ref name="mu"/> led by Andy Ayamiseba.<ref>Banoe, Pono. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=WlBqXSLgEWcC&pg=PA56 Kamus musik]''. Deresan, Yogyakarta: Penerbit Kanisius, 2003. p.</ref> Their music, sung in [[Tok Pisin]], and  originally in [[Bahasa Indonesia]] <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=avNqNqMstso</ref> included influences from [[reggae]] and political elements inspired by the Black Power movement.<ref name="mu">Gronow, Pekka, and Ilpo Saunio. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=paPRxPJ7jjEC&pg=PA184 An international history of the recording industry]''. London: Cassell, 1999. p. 184</ref><ref name="reg2">Hayward, Philip. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=0KRXtWHqqWMC&pg=PA109 Sound Alliances: Indigenous Peoples, Cultural Politics, and Popular Music in the Pacific]''. London: Cassell, 1998. p. 109</ref> The group went into voluntary exile in Vanuatu in 1979, protesting Indonesian policies in West Papua. They later moved to [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name="lock">Lockard, Craig A. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_likSSE9sEAC&pg=PA105 Dance of Life Popular Music and Politics in Southeast Asia]''. Honolulu, HI: University of Hawaiʻi Press, 1998. p. 105</ref>

Black Brothers were the most popular musical group in [[New Guinea]] during the 1980s.<ref name="mu"/> The reggae influences of the Black Brothers influenced various other musical groups in Papua New Guinea.<ref name="reg2"/>

There was another group titled 'Black Brothers' in [[New Caledonia]], which was associated with the [[Kanak people|Kanak]] independence movement.<ref name="reg">Hayward, Philip. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=0KRXtWHqqWMC&pg=PA50 Sound Alliances: Indigenous Peoples, Cultural Politics, and Popular Music in the Pacific]''. London: Cassell, 1998. pp. 50, 60</ref>

