[[File:Thiakry 2013.jpg|thumb|Thiakry from Senegal]] [[File:Gambia Chakery 0001.jpg|thumb|Thiakry from Gambia]]
'''Thiakry''' (also spelled '''thiacry''' or '''chakery''') is a sweet [[millet]] [[couscous]] dish eaten in [[West Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celtnet.org.uk/recipes/miscellaneous/fetch-recipe.php?rid=misc-thiacry |title=Desserts - Thiacry | publisher=celtnet | accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.easy-healthy-recipes-for-kids.com/couscous-recipe.html |title=Thiacry - Couscous Recipe | publisher=easy-healthy-recipes-for-kids.com | accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref> The wheat or millet granules are mixed with milk, sweetened condensed milk, or yogurt, as well as dried fruit such as [[raisins]], [[desiccated coconut]], and spices such as [[nutmeg]].
