{{Merge|Water supply and women in developing countries |discuss=Talk:Water access and gender#Merger| date=April 2018 }}

'''Water access and gender''' are intricately linked in many parts of the world today and also historically. Discrimination in access to water occurs along many lines, including [[gender]]. Women and girls are more likely to be expected to collect and provide water for their families in less developed countries. Men and women are affected differently by water crisis situations. The study of how water access and gender are related is part of [[Feminist political ecology]] (FPE). Dealing with inequalities of water access falls under [[international human rights law]].

== Women and water access ==
[[File:DRAWING_WATER_TO_QUENCH_THURST.jpg|alt=Woman collecting water in Kenya.|thumb|Woman collecting water in Kenya.]]
Around the world there are patterns of [[discrimination]] in relation to water access.{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=557}} Around 1.1 billion people in the world do not have access to adequate water supplies.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Moser|first=Anne|date=2009-01-01|title=Women and Water: Marginalization, Hope and a Call to Action|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-200881508.html|journal=Feminist Collections: A Quarterly of Women's Studies Resources|volume=|pages=|subscription=yes|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> In many places of the world, getting and providing water is considered "women's work," so [[gender]] and water access are intricately linked.{{sfn|Keefer|Bousalis|2015|p=256}} Also, because collecting water is often unpaid labor, women are more likely to be assigned to water collection.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Strochlic|first=Nina|date=April 2017|title=Water Collective|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=121884321&site=ehost-live|journal=National Geographic|volume=231|issue=4|pages=24|subscription=yes|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>  Water gathering and supply to family units remains primarily a woman’s task in [[less developed countries]] where water gathering is considered a main chore.{{sfn|Keefer|Bousalis|2015|p=256}} This water work is also largely unpaid household work based on patriarchal gender norms and often related to domestic work, such as laundry, cooking and childcare.<ref name="Bennet et al 2008">{{cite journal|last1=Bennet|first1=Vivienne|last2=Davila-Poblete|first2=Sonia|last3=Rico|first3=Maria N.|date=2008|title=Water and gender: the unexpected connection that really matters.|journal=Journal of International Affairs|volume=61|issue=2|pages=107-126}}</ref>{{sfn|Koolwal|Van de Walle|2010|p=5}} Areas that rely on women to primarily collect water include countries in [[Africa]], [[South Asia]] and in the [[Middle East]].{{sfn|Koolwal|Van de Walle|2010|p=4}}

Many women in less developed countries must walk long distances to collect water.{{sfn|Keefer|Bousalis|2015|p=261}} Girls who must spend hours a day collecting water from natural sources often miss school.<ref name=":1" /> Many walk miles to get to the water source and must wait in line for their turn to collect water.<ref name=":1" /> Some women in Africa may spend eight hours a day both collecting and then treating the water.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McManus|first=Reed|date=November 2014|title=One Woman at a Time|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=hxh&AN=102926262&site=ehost-live|journal=Sierra|volume=99|issue=6|pages=44|subscription=yes|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref> In areas of [[Nairobi]], women carry 44 pound containers of water back to their homes, taking anywhere between an hour and several hours to wait and collect the water.{{sfn|Crow|Odaba|2010|p=733}} Some of these women are unable to open their businesses because of the wait for collecting water.{{sfn|Crow|Odaba|2010|p=745}}

Women and girls who collect water may also face [[sexual assault]] along the way.{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=557}}

In places like [[Nepal]], not only are women and girls affected by water collection by it being their "job," but there are also restrictions for collecting water based on [[caste]].<ref name=":1" /> [[India]] also has a great deal of social stratification that not only affect water gathering, but also effect policies relating to government-managed water services.{{sfn|Deininger|Nag|Nagarajan|2011|p=343}} When women are represented in the government, local women are more likely to participate in public meetings relating to water delivery.{{sfn|Deininger|Nag|Nagarajan|2011|p=347}} In rural Bangladesh, women living in poverty are less likely to have a political voice regarding water access.{{sfn|Sultana|2007|p=498}} When inequalities to water access aren't properly addressed, governments end up providing a low level of service to their people.{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=558}}

In addition, [[Water scarcity|Water crises]] affect men and women differently in some areas, such as in rural [[Bangladesh]].{{sfn|Sultana|2007|p=494}} 

== Men and water access ==
Beginning in the 19th century, water management, access, and technology was considered a masculine domain.<ref name="Bennet et al 2008" />

Gender norms can negatively affect how men and women access water through such behavior expectations along gender lines--for example, when water collection is a woman’s chore, men who collect water may face [[discrimination]] for performing perceived women’s work.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=CAP-NET|last2=GWA|date=2006|title=Why Gender Matters: a tutorial for water managers|location=Delft|publisher=CAP-NET International network for Capacity Building in Integrated Water Resources Management}}</ref> Men rarely collect water in rural [[Bangladesh]] due to local ideas of [[masculinity]].{{sfn|Sultana|2007|p=496}} On the other hand, the same norms often result in women being pressured to collect and use water in an efficient and timely manner, without the advantages of modern technology.<ref name="Krish 2011">{{cite journal|last1=Krishnaraj|first1=Maithreyi|date=2011|title=Women and water: Issues of gender, caste, class and institutions|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|volume=46|issue=18|pages=37-39}}</ref> A study conducted in the [[Volta Region]] of [[Ghana]] found that men collected water only when their wives were not available.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arku|first=Frank S.|date=July 2010|title=Time savings from easy access to clean water: Implications for rural men's and women's well-being|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=bth&AN=51431946&site=ehost-live|journal=Progress In Development Studies|volume=10|pages=238|subscription=yes|via=EBSCOhost}}</ref>

Boys and girls are able to more fully participate in school when there is improved access to water.{{sfn|Koolwal|Van de Walle|2010|p=24}}

== Addressing inequalities in access ==
[[Feminist political ecology|Feminist political ecology (FPE)]] seeks to question and inform understanding regarding how gender, and other social labels and classifiers, influence how people relate to and interact with the natural environment, including how people have access to water.<ref name="Oberhauser et al 2017 general">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DHE3DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=feminist%20spaces%20gender%20and%20geography%20in%20a%20global&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=feminist%20spaces%20gender%20and%20geography%20in%20a%20global&f=false|title=Feminist Spaces: Gender and Geography in a Global Context|last1=Oberhauser|first1=Ann M.|last2=Fluri|first2=Jennifer L.|last3=Whitson|first3=Risa|last4=Mollett|first4=Sharlene|date=2017|publisher=Taylor and Francis|year=|isbn=|location=Florence|pages=}}</ref><ref name="Ivens 2008">{{cite journal|last1=Ivens|first1=Saskia|date=2008|title=Does increased water access empower women?|journal=Development|volume=51|pages=63-67}}</ref> Gender becomes integrated into these environmentally-focused and development-oriented policies, projects, and programs through [[gender mainstreaming]], which further encourages the convergence of [[Feminism|women’s issues]] and [[gender equality]] with [[natural resource]] protection and development projects.<ref name="Dankelman 2010">{{cite book|title=Gender and Climate Change: An Introduction|last1=Dankelman|first1=Irene|date=2010|publisher=Taylor and Francis|location=New York}}</ref>

Addressing inequalities in access to water is also considered a [[human rights]] issue in legal terms and in [[International human rights law|international human rights laws]].{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=563}}{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=567}} Equality in water access also means that governments and [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental organizations]] need to focus on the most disadvantaged and poorest members of the community.{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=565}} The [[United Nations]] adopted a resolution in 2010 on the "[[Human right to water and sanitation|Human Right to Water and Sanitation]]."{{sfn|Winkler|Satterthwaite|De Albuquerque|2014|p=566}}

